Every Christological "conspiracy" is factually wrong, but I like how each offers a heretical flavor, with its own vices and ameliorations. Gen X liked a very ridiculous one, that Christ was the son of Caesar and Cleopatra. That one reveals an inherent "royalty", world-importance.

Millennials preferred The Virgin having other children except Christ, and also Christ taking St. Mary Magdalene as a wife. Those are the most repulsive trains of thought to me. Ultimately it just seeks to "strip down" divinity, turn all celestial figures into a "regular" people.

The former is just a slight pride, a catkilling curiosity to reveal some secret that is not there, so it has to be invented. The latter is worse. It's a soup of complexes, weak men striving to *remake* Scripture into their own neurotic image. Normie-fication, in 4channish speech.
